annotation.notes: Descriptive text or notes about an item (e.g. in an annotated bibliography)

article.notes: Should be prepended to the section field (e.g., article I section 3)

crossref.notes: Inherits data from a parent entry.

entrysubtype.notes: May be used to determine the entry type (article-magazine).

howpublished.notes: Check if a URL is contained.

journalsubtitle.notes: It should be concatenated to the `container-title`.

langid.notes: The language id of the bibliography entry. The identifier must be a language name known to the babel/polyglossia packages. It should be converted to ISO 639-1 language code in CSL.

language.notes: The `language` field in `biblatex` has no special internal meaning thus it is used only when langid is missing.

number.notes: This field is used as `issue` in `article` type or `collection-number` with `collection-title` in `book` type. It is also `number` in `@patent` or `@report`.

organization.notes: The `organizer` that sponsors a conference or a `publisher` that publishes a `@manual` or `@online`.

pubstate.notes: The publication state of the work, e. g., ‘in press’.

relatedstring.notes: The style apa.csl assumes that `genre` is entered as “Review of the book” or similar.

shorthand.notes: A special designation to be used by the citation style instead of the usual label.

xref.notes: Establishes a parent-child relationship in biblatex, but without inheriting data => no need to parse this.

ibmjrd.value: IBM Journal of Research and Development

ieeetcad.value: IEEE Transactions on Computer-Aided Design of Integrated Circuits

jcss.value: Journal of Computer and System Sciences

toois.value: ACM Transactions on Office Information Systems

toplas.value: ACM Transactions on Programming Languages and Systems

article.notes: May also be `article-magazine` or `article-newspaper` depending upon the field `entrysubtype`.

audio.notes: CSL's `song` can be used for any audio recording (not only music).

comment.notes: Special entry type for Scribe compatibility

inpress.notes: Use for preprints, working papers, and similar works posted on a platform where some level of persistence or stewardship is expected (e.g. arXiv or other preprint repositories, working paper series).

jurisdiction.notes: "Court decisions, court recordings, and similar things."

legislation.notes: "Laws, bills, legislative proposals, and similar things." May also be `bill`

legmaterial.notes: APA §11.6: Legislative materials include federal testimony, hearings, bills, resolutions, reports, and related documents.

manual.notes: CSL's `report` is also used for manuals and similar technical documentation (e.g. a software, instrument, or test manual).

preamble.notes: Special entry type for inserting commands or text in the bbl

preprint.notes: Use for preprints, working papers, and similar works posted on a platform where some level of persistence or stewardship is expected (e.g. arXiv or other preprint repositories, working paper series).

presentation.notes: A speech or other presentation (e.g. a paper, talk, poster, or symposium at a conference).

review.notes: "A more specific variant of the `@article` type"

string.notes: Special entry type for defining abbreviations

suppbook.notes: lossy mapping; "Supplemental material in a `@book`. This type is closely related to the @inbook entry type. While `@inbook` is primarily intended for a part of a book with its own title (e. g., a single essay in a collection of essays by the same author), this type is provided for elements such as prefaces, introductions, forewords, afterwords, etc. which often have a generic title only. Style guides may require such items to be formatted differently from other `@inbook` items."

unpublished.notes: For unpublished works not made widely available or only hosted on personal websites, use manuscript

xdata.notes: special item type: "`@xdata` entries hold data which may be inherited by other entries using the xdata field. Entries of this type only serve as data containers; they may not be cited or added to the bibliography."
